As the probability of survival increases, the percentage of the population that is young declines, the percentage of those retired increases, and the percentage of those who work may increase or decrease. For an infinitesimal increase inp, the percentage of those who work increases if
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $n/ ( n+l) > [ p/ ( 1+g) ] ^{l}$ \end{document}
            and decreases if the converse is true. As the growth rate of generations increases, the percentage of the population in the first stage of life increases, the percentage of the population in the third stage of life decreases, and the percentage of the population who work may increase or decrease. For an infinitesimal increase ing, the percentage of the population that is in the second stage of life increases if
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $n/ ( n+l) < [ p/ ( 1+g) ] ^{l}$ \end{document}
            .

