fn.p:
The data fit a lognormal process better over a long horizon rather than a random walk in levels. However, as in Caballero (1991), we would like to use the solution in the model. Taking a linear approximation to the lognormal process around a zero growth rate results, for example, in a dividend process as follows:
                        \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $D_{t+1}=D_{t}+D_{t}\varepsilon _{t}$ \end{document}
                     . Consequently, the values used in our numerical example give a fairly good estimate of the drift and standard deviation.

