fn.p:
These numerical exercises should be taken to be suggestive theoretical exercises. One may think that it is unreasonable to expect a change in the probability of surviving from .985 to .98, which implies a change in the expected life span of 67 years to 50 years. In fact, one is more likely to believe that people are now living longer, and so we are more likely to see an increase inp. When
                        \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $p=\mathrm{.}\,987$ \end{document}
                     , the expected life span is 77 years. For the change ingwe obtain large changes in asset prices, but one may also question whether we can realistically expect population growth to increase by that degree. The point is that any change to any parameter that affects the young population greatly will have a large effect on asset prices.

